<HEADLINE>
<P>
MOVIES TO TAPE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Kevin Thomas 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Hells Angels on Wheels (TNT Sunday at 9 p.m., Monday at 11 a.m.), a stylish 
but raw display of sex and violence from Richard Rush, is a 1967 biker flick 
made with the approval of the Hells Angels.Terrific performances from Adam 
Roarke, Jack Nicholson and Sabrina Scharf. 
</P>
<P>
 Black Rainbow (TMC Sunday at 12:10 p.m.), Mike Hodges' 1989 psychic-thriller 
with ecological undertones, is one of the most original independent films of 
recent years. Rosanna Arquette is a commanding presence as a young medium who 
develops terrifying powers of prophecy. With Tom Hulce and Jason Robards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Motion Picture Review 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA091894-0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 080176 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
September 18, 1994, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
TV Times; Page 6; Television Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
408 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
PRIME-TIME FLICKS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Kevin Thomas 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Lethal Weapon 2 (CBS Sunday at 9 p.m.) again has Mel Gibson and Danny Glover 
as a cop team, but this 1989 sequel is outrageously overscaled and has the 
brain-rattling pace of a speed freak going the wrong way on a freeway. This 
time, Gibson and Glover go after a drug kingpin operating under diplomatic 
immunity. 
</P>
<P>
 KTLA presents four 8 p.m. airings of Clint Eastwood movies, starting Monday 
with Play Misty for Me, which marked Eastwood's assured 1971 directorial debut. 
Eastwood stars as a Monterey Bay deejay stalked by a deranged fan (a bravura 
turn by Jessica Walters). 
</P>
<P>
 While this film shows the lean, taut influence of director Don Siegel (who 
appears briefly), Eastwood's surreal 1973 Western High Plains Drifter (Tuesday, 
again Saturday at 7 p.m.) echoes Eastwood's other mentor, Sergio Leone, who 
directed him to stardom in a series of '60s spaghetti Westerns. Indeed, 
Eastwood once again becomes Leone's "The Stranger," as the steely, monosyllabic 
sharpshooter of "Drifter." His mission is to face down three gunmen on their 
way to wipe out a frontier town. This stylized allegory, chillingly 
paranoid,atmospheric and filled with sardonic humor, is as ambiguous as it is 
violent -- and much like a samurai movie. 
</P>
<P>
 Directed by John Sturges and written by Elmore Leonard, Joe Kidd (Wednesday) 
is a solidly crafted 1972 Western that forthrightly depicts injustices to 
Mexican Americans. Robert Duvall and John Saxon co-star with Eastwood, who is 
hired by land owner Duvall to track down some Mexican Americans. 
</P>
<P>
 Don Siegel's wry, witty Coogan's Bluff (Thursday), the first of the five 
Siegel-Eastwood collaborations, turns Southwestern lawman Eastwood loose on 
Manhattan's mean streets. 
</P>
<P>
 Omen IV: The Awakening (KTTV Tuesday at 8 p.m.), a 1991 TV movie, extends the 
legacy of Damien, the Son of Satan, with decidedly diminishing returns. 
</P>
<P>
 Crocodile Dundee II (ABC Saturday at 8 p.m.) is almost as much fun the second 
time around. As an adventure, this 1988 release is nothing special, yet it 
again shows to advantage the tremendously likable Paul Hogan, who this time out 
must rescue his journalist girlfriend (again Linda Kozlowski) from a Colombian 
drug kingpin. 
</P>
<P>
 John Ford's dark-hued 1947 The Fugitive (KCET Saturday at 9 p.m.) finds a 
revolutionary priest coming into conflict with the man who once extended him 
hospitality. Henry Fonda, Dolores Del Rio and Pedro Armendariz star; Gabriel 
Figueroa was the film's great cameraman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Motion Picture Review 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA091894-0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 080177 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
September 18, 1994, Sunday, Orange County Edition 
</P>
