</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
IN BRIEF: NONFICTION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DICK RORABACK 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 TALKING PICTURES: With the People Who Made Them, edited by Sylvia Shorris and 
Marion Bundy (The New Press: $25; 400 pp.) It was a nice notion.It just didn't 
quite come off. The idea was to chat up some movie hands -- property masters 
and producers, grips and gaffers -- on how it was in a Hollywood of softer 
edges. A labor of love, really, and not too soon: Of 38 film people 
interviewed, 17 died before the book was published. The trouble is in the 
telling. Not that the old-timers are necessarily less-gifted raconteurs than 
vox pop. at large. Some are spellbinders. Some aren't. That said, eavesdrop on 
some of the more colorful chroniclers of foretime: 
</P>
<P>
 William Fadiman, story editor: "Harry Cohn, the head of Columbia Pictures, had 
an offer for the studio. I said, 'Harry, why don't you accept it? You'd have a 
lot more money.' He said, 'But who would invite me to dinner?' " Eleanor 
Wolquitt, reader: "They hired me to help (German writer Curt Siodmak) with the 
English idiom for 'Tarzan and the Fountain of Youth.' Like 'Me Tarzan, you 
Jane,' I suppose, instead of 'Ich Tarzan, du Jane.' " 
</P>
<P>
 On second thought, there's more than a chuckle, and instructive, too. Herbert 
Wrench, editor: "I needed some men laughing and I couldn't find anything right, 
so I went down to the library and got some chickens clucking and ran it 
backwards. I put it in there and nobody knew." That's entertainment! 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Book Review 
</P>
