</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 THE MIDNIGHT FLUTE: Chinese Poems of Love and Longing, translated from the 
Chinese by Sam Hamill (Shambala: $11; 150 pp., illustrated, paperback 
original). Because the Imperial government forbade scholar-officials to serve 
in their native provinces, parting and separation became important motifs in 
Chinese poetry. This mini-anthology of Hamill's satisfying translations offers 
Western readers an overview of more than 1,000 years of verse. The poems tend 
to be allusive, formal and reserved in tone: Contemplating his own mortality, 
Li Po (701-762), wrote, "We sit together, the mountain and me,/ until only the 
mountain remains." 
</P>
