<TEXT>
<P>
 Mexican crooner Luis Miguel's "Segundo Romance" continues to be one of the 
dominant albums on the Times' Southern California pop chart, landing at No. 7. 
Some predicted a big drop-off, dismissing last week's No. 5 debut as an 
aberration. But the two-notch descent is fairly insignificant. Miguel's album 
is the clear leader on the Latin album chart, both in Southern California and 
nationally. Another unusual Top 10 entry, that live "3 Tenors" pop-classical 
