<HEADLINE>
<P>
ALBUM REVIEW 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Ernest Hardy 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 ***; SPEARHEAD, "Home" ( Capitol ) 
</P>
<P>
 On his past efforts, with the groups the Beatnigs and the critically lauded 
Disposable Heroes of Hiphoprisy, the street poetry of Spearhead's Michael 
Franti was couched in punk, thrash and industrial grooves that were punctuated 
with elements of hip-hop. With "Home," the debut album from his latest group, 
the music is a more accessible blend of rap, R&B and folk. 
</P>
<P>
 Many rap artists invoke the name of Gil Scott-Heron when citing primary 
influences, but few have a claim as valid as Franti's. Possessing a deep, 
caramel-smooth voice that resembles the elder word-man's, Franti pushes the 
similarity even further with his socially themed lyrics. Tackling issues such 
as AIDS, racism, social apathy and poverty, Franti uses both fierce 
intelligence and compassion to blur the lines between personal and universal 
concerns. In the past, his wordiness often drifted into preachiness. With 
"Home," however, he tempers the politics with a real soulfulness, securing his 
position as one of hip-hop's brightest hopes. 
</P>
<P>
 New albums are rated on a scale of one star (poor), two stars (fair), three 
stars (good) and four stars (excellent).  
</P>
<P>
 Ernest Hardy 
</P>
</TEXT>
