<HEADLINE>
<P>
CRITIC'S PICK: 'A FRIENDSHIP IN VIENNA' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Lynne Heffley 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 This 1988 TV film is that rare pleasure -- a family film of maturity and 
substance.Based on Doris Orgel's book "Devil in Vienna," Richard Alfieri's 
sensitive teleplay chronicles a friendship between two 13-year-old girls -- one 
Jewish (Jenny Lewis), one Catholic (Kamie Harper) -- that endures through 
Germany's annexation of Austria in 1938. Without a breath of false 
sentimentality, Alfierei script reveals what childhood becomes in the face of 
oppression and what uncompromising integrity means in the name of friendship. 
Under Arthur Allan Seidelman's direction, the cast -- which includes Edward 
Asner and Jane Alexander -- is flawless (Disney Channel at 7 p.m., Monday at 3 
a.m.). Lynne Heffley 
</P>
</TEXT>
