<HEADLINE>
<P>
CRITIC'S PICK: 'UN COEUR EN HIVER' (A HEART IN WINTER) 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Kenneth Turan 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Once again, French director Claude Sautet succeeds in finding surprisingly 
supple and involving romantic entanglements in the well-upholstered lives of 
the bourgeoisie.Gregarious and sure of himself, Maxime (Andre Dussolier), 
proprietor of a prestigious violin repair shop, has fallen rapturously in love 
with a beautiful young violinist (Emmanuelle Beart). But she and Maxime's 
employee (Daniel Auteuil, pictured), a meticulous, diffident craftsman, are 
apparently on the same wavelength. An excursion to some of the wilder shores of 
love and obsession, this 1993 release proves its statement, "feelings can't be 
demystified," with every scene (Cinemax Wednesday at 8 p.m.). Kenneth Turan 
</P>
