<HEADLINE>
<P>
COLLEGE FOOTBALL / SPOTLIGHT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
Compiled by Thomas Bonk, Bob Cuomo and Emilio Garcia-Ruiz 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 TELL LUTHER AND CHRISTINE 
</P>
<P>
 So what was so significant, besides the score, in Penn State's 61-21 wipeout 
of Iowa? 
</P>
<P>
 Joe Paterno's wonderful shades? Hayden Fry finally admitting he allows Craig 
T. Nelson to borrow his name to play Hayden Fox in "Coach"? 
</P>
<P>
 Nope. Something more trivial. It was the first-ever regular-season matchup 
between Division I coaches with 200 victories. And Paterno won it. He now has 
260 victories in 29 seasons and Fry has 202 in 33. BET MRS. FIELDS GOT IN 
</P>
<P>
 The Big Snub Award goes to Amos Lawrence, but that would mean some recognition 
for the former North Carolina running back and that would disqualify him. So 
let's just say that if there actually was a Big Snub Award, Lawrence's 
achievements would go unnoticed, automatically earning him the title. 
</P>
<P>
 Anyway, they retired the uniform numbers of 14 former Tar Heel football stars 
in ceremonies before North Carolina's 49-0 shutout of Tulane at Chapel Hill, 
but Lawrence's No. 20 was not among them. 
</P>
<P>
 This seemed a curious oversight to many, including Lawrence, an elementary 
school physical education teacher in Virginia. After all, he set 18 school 
records and is one of only two collegians (Tony Dorsett is the other) to rush 
for at least 1,000 yards each year at a school. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's all mind-boggling to me," The News & Observer of Raleigh quoted 
Lawrence, known as "Famous Amos." 
</P>
<P>
 Memo to "Famous Amos": That's the way the cookie crumbles. WHY NOTHING'S WRONG 
WITH THREE YARDS, CLOUD OF DUST 
</P>
<P>
 The best reason for sticking with the running game was presented by the LSU 
Tigers, who had three passes intercepted and run back for touchdowns in the 
fourth quarter and lost to Auburn, 30-26. 
</P>
<P>
 Said Auburn Coach Terry Bowden: "The second guessers and people in retrospect 
are going to have plenty of things to say." 
</P>
<P>
 The second-guessers will descend upon LSU Coach Curley Hallman, who said he 
probably should have called a few more running plays, especially since he had a 
23-9 lead in the fourth quarter. 
</P>
<P>
 Said Hallman: "You go back in hindsight, would I do it differently? Yeah, 
probably on a lot of 'em. Maybe I'll learn from this. Yeah, in hindsight, I 
would go back and run it." NOW, A LITTLE SOMETHING FOR YOU BASEBALL FANS 
</P>
<P>
 Utah State beat Ohio University, 5-0, in Athens, Ohio, on a field goal and a 
safety. 
</P>
<P>
 Try as it might, Ohio University couldn't get to first base. AND THEY'LL DO IT 
FAST 
</P>
<P>
 Pittsburgh's 27-3 loss to Ohio State was a simple matter of physics. How else 
can you interpret Pittsburgh quarterback Sean Fitzgerald's explanation of a 
27-3 loss to Ohio State? 
</P>
<P>
 Said Fitzgerald: "Big fast guys will beat small fast guys." NOTEWORTHY 
</P>
<P>
 -- Auburn has the nation's longest winning streak, 14 games. 
</P>
<P>
 -- Coach Larry Smith's winning streak at Missouri reached one. The Tigers 
ended a 17-game, four-year road losing streak with a 17-0 victory at Houston. 
</P>
<P>
 -- Tim Murphy of Harvard, who took over when Joe Restic retired after 23 
seasons, became the first Harvard coach to win his opening game since Art 
Valpey in 1948. 
</P>
<P>
 -- Steve Stenstrom tied Jim Plunkett as Stanford's winningest quarterback as 
the Cardinal defeated San Jose State, 51-20. Stenstrom got his 22nd victory. 
</P>
<P>
 -- UNLV receiver Randy Gatewood set the NCAA I-A record for most catches and 
yards in a game. He had 23 receptions for 363 yards in a 48-38 loss to Idaho. 
</P>
<P>
 -- Grambling defeated Morgan State by a mere 75 points, 87-12. DOUBLE YOUR 
PLEASURE 
</P>
<P>
 Grady Benton passed for 560 yards and a school-record eight touchdowns as West 
Texas A&M outscored Howard Payne, 59-56. 
</P>
<P>
 Benton, a transfer from Arizona State, completed 41 of 69 passes, including 
three touchdowns to Brian Bailey. Benton also threw two touchdown passes to 
Brian's twin brother, Brad Bailey. FOR THE 100TH ANNIVERSARY THEY SWEAR 
SOMEBODY WINS 
</P>
<P>
 The oldest big-school football rivalry west of the Allegheny Mountains is 
what? Take a guess. Uh, uh, you're wrong. 
</P>
<P>
 It's Cincinnati vs. Miami of Ohio, two schools that have been knocking each 
other all over the football field for 99 years. Miami of Ohio leads the series, 
53-39-7, the latest tie occurring at Oxford, Ohio, on Miami's 37-yard field 
goal into a gusting wind as time ran out. 
</P>
<P>
 Jon Bacon kicked a school-record 58-yard field goal for the Bearcats. Final 
score: Cincinnati 17, Miami, Ohio, 17. WHERE THERE'S A WILL, I GUESS THERE'S A 
WAY 
</P>
<P>
 How did SMU Coach Tom Rossley explain a 34-31 victory over New Mexico? 
</P>
<P>
 "The players willed themselves to win," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 Oh, well, of course. If it was that simple, they ought to expand the scope of 
their powers. Maybe they should try willing themselves to ace trig class. THE 
STORY FOR CYCLONES: NOT WINDLESS, BUT WINLESS 
</P>
<P>
 Well, looking at that old clock on the wall, it might be about time that 
somebody asks Jim Walden to start packing his bags. 
</P>
<P>
 The Iowa State coach is 0-3 this season, 28-50-2 since he came to the campus 
in Ames, Iowa, in 1987 and has had one winning season. 
</P>
<P>
 The Cyclones' latest defeat was to Western Michigan. This happened despite, 
according to an Associated Press report, a "tricky Cyclone Stadium wind." 
</P>
<P>
 It might be blowing one way now. Whatever woes Walden had, they're stacked 
even higher now. He lost his top two quarterbacks to injuries and finished the 
game with former walk-on defensive back Jeff St. Clair at the position. YOU 
CAN'T SHUCK ALCORN; AIR MCNAIR STILL FLYING 
</P>
<P>
 Here is the Steve McNair update: Alabama State held Alcorn State's star 
quarterback to less than 600 yards total offense for the first time this 
season. 
</P>
<P>
 McNair earned 452 yards total offense, 344 yards with his passing, in Alcorn's 
39-7 victory at Lorman, Miss. 
</P>
<P>
 Alcorn State is a Division I-AA school. WHAT DID YOU EXPECT FROM A BUNCH OF 
TURTLES? 
</P>
<P>
 Allen Williams of Maryland rushed for 163 yards in a 24-13 victory over West 
Virginia and it was nearly 100 yards more than the Terrapins had managed in 
their two previous games. 
</P>
<P>
 Maryland was averaging 33.5 yards rushing a game, but Williams came close to 
matching that average on one play -- a 25-yard touchdown run. IT'S A MATH 
PROBLEM: YOU KNOW, LONG DIVISION 
</P>
<P>
 So you like playing with the Big Boys? Northeast Louisiana, a former I-AA 
power playing in Division I-A for the first time this season, got drubbed, 
70-6, by Georgia in Athens, Ga. 
</P>
<P>
 The Indians are 0-3. 
</P>
<P>
 It was Georgia's biggest victory since beating The Citadel, 76-0, in 1958 and 
the worst setback for the Indians since a 63-0 loss at Cincinnati in 1977. BUT 
IT'LL LOOK LIKE A LINE DRIVE IN THE BOX SCORE 
</P>
<P>
 Virginia overcame seven turnovers and nine penalties to defeat Clemson 9-6. 
</P>
<P>
 The Cavaliers were in well, bad company, all right. Oklahoma overcame 11 
turnovers and three lost fumbles to defeat Texas Tech, 17-11. SOMETIMES IT'S SO 
EASY (AND SOMETIMES IT'S NOT) 
</P>
<P>
 -- Last year, Boston College and Virginia Tech combined for 1,126 yards as the 
Eagles won, 48-34. The same two teams managed 468 yards this time as the Hokies 
avenged last year's loss, 12-7. 
</P>
<P>
 -- Nebraska last year gained only 208 yards rushing against UCLA but had 234 
yards on the ground by halftime this time. The Cornhuskers totaled 484 yards on 
the ground in their 49-21 victory over the Bruins. 
</P>
<P>
 -- Notre Dame was held to 60 yards rushing in the first half of its 21-20 
victory over Michigan State. The Irish piled up 209 yards in the second half as 
they came from behind to win. THEY CAME, THEY SAW THEY DIDN'T LOSE 
</P>
<P>
 We hear enough about the heroes. Let's have a cheer for the doormats. Better 
make these former doormats, though. You probably won't have these guys to wipe 
your cleats on anymore. 
</P>
<P>
 -- Kent broke major-college football's longest losing streak, beating Akron, 
32-15, for its first victory in 18 games. 
</P>
<P>
 -- Northwestern beat Air Force, 14-10, to end a 10-game winless drought. 
</P>
<P>
 -- SMU broke a six-game home losing streak with its victory over New Mexico. 
DUCKS' HOME CROWD NOT WHAT IT'S QUACKED UP TO BE 
</P>
<P>
 The 25,358 in Eugene who came to watch Oregon's 34-16 loss to Utah represented 
the Ducks' smallest home crowd in 10 years. HOW THE TOP 25 FARED 
</P>
<P>
 RANK: 1 
</P>
<P>
 TEAM: Florida (3-0) 
</P>
<P>
 SYNOPSIS: Defeated Tennessee, 31-0; After this, Gators don't figure to be 
tested until they play Auburn at home on Oct. 15 and Georgia at home on Oct. 
29. Then it's up to Florida State on Nov. 26. 
</P>
<P>
 NEXT: at Mississippi, Oct. 1 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
