<P>
DUKES BEAT CANADIANS, WIN THE PACIFIC COAST LEAGUE TITLE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Don Barbara drove in the winning run with a sacrifice fly in the sixth inning 
as the Albuquerque Dukes beat the Vancouver Canadians, 3-2, on Saturday to win 
the Pacific Coast League title. 
</P>
<P>
 Al Osuna pitched 3 2/3 innings of one-hit relief and Antonio Osuma got the 
final two outs for the save. 
</P>
<P>
 Albuquerque beat Vancouver, 2-0, in 11 innings on Friday night to force the 
fifth game. 
</P>
<P>
 The Dukes, managed by former Dodger catcher Rick Dempsey, are the top farm 
club of the Dodgers, and the Canadians are the Angels' triple-A team. 
</P>
<P>
 Albuquerque took a 1-0 lead in the first inning on Ron Coomer's infield 
groundout. Vancouver tied the score in the fourth on designated hitter Luis 
Raven's leadoff homer and took the lead on P.J. Forbes' sacrifice fly in the 
fifth. 
</P>
<P>
 Billy Ashley tied the score in the sixth with an RBI groundout before 
Barbara's sacrifice fly. 
</P>
<P>
 Vancouver starter Shad Williams took the loss. 
</P>
