<HEADLINE>
<P>
VENTURA IS MORE THAN RESPECTFUL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BRYAN RODGERS, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Ventura College spent most of last season as a doormat for opposing teams. The 
Pirates scored only 40 points and finished 0-10. 
</P>
<P>
 So when Antelope Valley came visiting Saturday night, Ventura Coach George 
Rosales was thinking about payback and respect. 
</P>
<P>
 Rosales hit the jackpot, as Ventura defeated Antelope Valley, 20-12, in a 
nonconference game at Ventura High. 
</P>
<P>
 The victory -- the Pirates' second in a row -- avenged last year's 35-0 loss 
to Antelope Valley (0-2). 
</P>
<P>
 "Now we have got some confidence that we can play," Rosales said. "We beat a 
pretty good football team tonight." 
</P>
<P>
 A pair of first-quarter touchdowns staked Ventura to a 14-0 lead. Ivan McCrae 
scored on a four-yard run and Ira Brown caught a five-yard pass from Aaron 
Trianna. 
</P>
<P>
 Antelope Valley countered with a drive in the second quarter. Roosevelt Miller 
scored on a one-yard run for the Marauders to trim the lead to 14-6. Matrai 
Zoltan's kick was wide left. 
</P>
<P>
 Ventura running backs McCrae and Gordy Abellera combined for 157 rushing 
yards. 
</P>
<P>
 Trianna was seven of 20 for 61 yards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
