<HEADLINE>
<P>
CUBA TO LET FARMERS SELL PRODUCE IN MARKETS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 In a sharp break with past policy, the Cuban government will soon allow 
farmers to sell produce in markets where supply and demand will determine 
prices. 
</P>
<P>
 The policy was announced in an interview published in Saturday's Granma 
newspaper with Cuba's number two-leader, Gen. Raul Castro, brother of President 
Fidel Castro. 
</P>
<P>
 Raul Castro said Cuba's 60,000 small private farms, state farms and 
cooperatives will be free to sell produce at the new markets after they fulfill 
their commitments to the state purchasing agency. 
</P>
