<HEADLINE>
<P>
BOOK REVIEW; REALTY NEGOTIATION TACTICS MADE CLEAR; "SUCCESSFUL REAL ESTATE 
NEGOTIATION, REVISED EDITION" BY PETER G. MILLER AND DOUGLAS M. BREGMAN (HARPER 
PERENNIAL, NEW YORK, 1994: $13, 240 PP.)  
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Special to The Times 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Negotiation is critical to real estate success for buyers, sellers and their 
realty agents. However, except for this book, there is virtually no source to 
obtain information on realty negotiation tactics. 
</P>
<P>
 The authors have created an easy-to-understand book that applies negotiation 
strategies to everyday real estate situations. The book is filled with examples 
of the negotiation tactics being explained. 
</P>
<P>
 However, the book is not just about negotiation tactics. It's also filled with 
practical real estate strategies. For example, the authors explain why the 
issue of a home's physical condition is so important when negotiating the sales 
price and terms. Miller and Bregman share profitable home fix-up tips that not 
only add value to the home but also strengthen the seller's negotiation 
position. 
</P>
<P>
 Chapter topics include How the Negotiation System Really Works; Real Estate as 
a Package Deal; What Is a Contract; Customizing Forms: The Use of Addenda and 
Contingencies; Three Important Ideas for Real Estate Negotiators; The Wide 
World of Warranties; Easements, Covenants and Conditions; Pricing and Down 
Payments; Appraisals and Value; Co-Signers; Deeds; Termites; Deposits; 
Environmental Issues; Fixtures: What Stays and What Goes; Occupancy Agreements; 
Damages and Rescission, and Creating a Back-Up Contract. 
</P>
<P>
 Who should read this book? Just three categories of real estate people: 
buyers, sellers and real estate agents. This would make a great textbook for a 
mini-course on real estate negotiation because it is so complete. But it should 
also be required reading for home buyers and sellers before they make a 
purchase offer so they understand how the negotiation process really works. On 
my scale of one to 10, this book rates a solid gold 10. 
</P>
</TEXT>
